\begin_layout Subsection
Bushfire and heatwave weather patterns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The replication of the analysis comparing bushfire and heatwave weather
 patterns confirms the results found in Chapter 4.
 The results are robust for daily as well as seasonal time scales.
 The linkages with ENSO patterns also remain valid.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The daily composites are perhaps the most consistent results.
 For air temperature, using alternative bushfire and heatwave data shows
 that the differences in their weather patterns persist.
 Cold fronts remain the most important feature of fire weather.
 On the other hand persistent heat anomalies characterize heatwaves events.
 The relative humidity patterns confirm that heatwaves inVictoria present
 dry anomalies in this region, with wet anomlies in several other areas
 of the continent.
 During bushfires in Victoria, Australia is predominantly dry.
 The alternative data also is capable of reproducing the contrasting intensity
 of the wave patterns during bushfires and heatwaves.
 Heatwaves present more intense geopotential height anomalies than bushfires.
 These anomalies also confirm the more dynamic nature of fire weather.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a daily time scale, the results show that the intensity of the frontal
 activity is the most important feature of extreme fire weather in Victoria.
 Therefore, indices aiming to predict fire weather with days in advance
 should focus on metrics to evaluate the strength of cold fronts.
 This contradicts the current state of practise where the FFDI, an index
 whose most sensitive paramater is temperature, is the most commonly used
 tool for fire emergencies.
 Consequently, fire weather danger estimated by the FFDI might be misleading
 during heatwave events.
 This finding is a key message from this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternative indices based on the leading effect of frontal activity over
 extreme fire weather have already been published in the literature 
